{"title_page": "Phoenix Warner", "text_new": "{{Infobox soap character\n| image = Phoenix Raynor.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| name = Phoenix Warner\n| series = [[Shortland Street]]\n| portrayer = Geordie Holibar\n| first = 2 August 2010\n| last = 25 February 2020\n| gender = Male\n| alias =Phoenix Warner\n| age = \n| classification = [[List of Shortland Street characters#Current characters|Present; recurring]]\n| born = 2 September 1995\n| death =\n| Introducer = Steven Zanoski (2010)<br>Maxine Fleming (2019)\n| years = 2010\u201313, 2019\u201320\n| occupation = Artist\n| family =\n| father= [[Chris Warner]]\n| mother= [[Alison Raynor]]\n| halfbrothers= [[Frank Warner (Shortland Street)|Frank Warner]] <br>[[Finn Warner]]<br>[[Harry Warner (character)|Harry Warner]]<br>James Warner\n| halfsisters = [[Sass Warner]]<br>[[Trinity Kwan]]\n| sisters= \n| daughters= Amelie Warner\n| sons= \n| granddaughters= \n| grandsons=\n| grandfathers= [[Bruce Warner (character)|Sir Bruce Warner]]<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (1992)#Kevin Raynor|Kevin Raynor]]\n| grandmothers= [[Margot Warner|Margot, Lady Warner]] <br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (1992)#Irene Raynor|Irene Raynor]]\n| relatives = [[Cecile Worthington]] (great aunt)<br>Desmond Worthington (great uncle)<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (2003)#Garth Worthington|Garth Worthington]] (great uncle)<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (2010)#Brian Raynor|Brian Raynor]] (great uncle)\n| nephews=\n| nieces= \n| aunts= [[Amanda Warner]]\n| uncles= [[Guy Warner]]\n| cousins= [[Tuesday Warner]]<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters#P|Kelly Piper]] (possibly)\n}}\n\n'''Phoenix Warner''' (previously '''Raynor''')  is a fictional character on the [[New Zealand]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Shortland Street]]''. He has been portrayed by Geordie Holibar since his debut in the show's first ever 90 minute episode in August 2010. The character was introduced as the unknown son of long-standing character [[Chris Warner]] ([[Michael Galvin]]) and ex-wife [[Alison Raynor]] ([[Danielle Cormack]]).\n\n==Creation and casting==\nAfter creating the role, producers researched baby name trends throughout the nineties and decided upon the name; \"Phoenix\".<ref name=namegame>{{cite web|title=The Name Game|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/name-game-4984349|work=[[Shortland Street]]|publisher=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=24 July 2012|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69OE1kf5q|archivedate=24 July 2012}}</ref> Geordie Holibar, the grandson of former ''Shortland Street'' actor [[Liddy Holloway]] was cast<ref name=block>{{cite web |url= http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/new-kid-block-3688541 |title= New kid on the block - Shortland Street |publisher= [[Television New Zealand]] |accessdate= 3 October 2011|date=August 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63s8XyVKi|archivedate=12 December 2011}}</ref> and the character made his debut in the show's first-ever feature-length episode on 2 August 2010.<ref name=otherchildren>{{cite web |url= http://www.throng.co.nz/shortland-street/chris-warner-finally-has-other-children |title= Chris Warner finally has other children |publisher= Throng |date= 3 August 2010 |accessdate= 3 October 2011}}</ref> Holibar's uncle [[Joel Tobeck]] helped him prepare for the role as he had previously appeared in the mid-1990s.<ref name=generation>{{cite journal|title=Generation game|journal=New Zealand TV Guide|date=19 August 2010|author=Nealon, Sarah}}</ref> Initially Holibar shared a lot of scenes with on screen father, [[Michael Galvin]], but as his storylines developed, he ended up spending a lot more scenes with the fellow teenage characters.<ref name=settling>{{cite web|title=Settling into the Street|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/settling-into-street-4039563|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=February 2011|accessdate=12 December 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63s9IBsuC|archivedate=12 December 2011}}</ref> Holibar enjoyed acting alongside people his age, saying; \"I have lots of fun with Frankie [Adams] ([[Ula Levi]]), Tyler [Read] ([[Evan Cooper (Shortland Street)|Evan Cooper]]) and Pearl [McGlashan] ([[Jasmine Cooper]]). It's been cool working with people your own age because you know that you're all going through the same kind of thing.\"<ref name=settling/> Holibar noted the help he received from long time cast members, Galvin and [[Angela Bloomfield]], \"It's good just working with him and Angela who have been on the show for so long and they know where the cameras are, they know not to block your light. They know all the tricks.\"<ref name=mathstutor>{{cite journal|title=Maths tutor turns tables on Phoenix|journal=New Zealand TV Guide|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=19 April 2012|author=Smith, Janie}}</ref> Phoenix departed the show in 2013.<ref name=depart>{{cite web|title=Riding in Cars show coming to the North island|date=4 November 2016|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11741645}}</ref>\n\nHolibar reprised his role in 2019, with the character returning on 5 December 2019.<ref name=granddaddy>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street: Chris Warner is about to be a grandaddy|author=Robertson, Kate|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/118050274/shortland-street-chris-warner-is-about-to-be-a-grandaddy|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]}}</ref> Holibar had not returned to the set since departing 6 years beforehand but felt \"super welcome\" filming his first scenes.<ref name=return>{{cite web|title=Geordie Holibar returns as Phoenix Warner!|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/shows/shortland-street/cast/geordie-holibar|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=6 December 2019}}</ref> The character of Phoenix was said to undergo a more \"flawed\" character arc upon returning.<ref name=frankreturn>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street returns with Frank Warner's homecoming|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/tv-guide/118405740/shortland-street-returns-with-frank-warners-homecoming|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]|date=6 January 2020|author=Harvey, Kerry|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref> Holibar departed the soap again on 25th February 2020 after Phoenix steals 1 millon dollars from the hospital leaving Tess and his daughter behind.\n\n==Storylines==\nPhoenix was born to [[Alison Raynor]] ([[Danielle Cormack]]) and her divorced husband, [[Chris Warner]] ([[Michael Galvin]]). Alison decided to keep Phoenix a secret from Chris and the two lived in America. After Alison grew sick of the American schooling system, she and Phoenix travelled to New Zealand and lived on a farm. In November 2009 Alison died on a yacht and Phoenix was taken in by her uncle [[Brian Raynor|Brian]] ([[Ian Mune]]).\n\nChris learnt in August 2010 that Phoenix was his son and, after a DNA test, he adopted him. Phoenix struggled to get on with half brother [[Harry Warner (Shortland Street)|Harry]] ([[Reid Walker]]) but befriended [[Evan Cooper (character)|Evan Cooper]] (Tyler Read). New girl [[Ula Levi]] (Frankie Adams) spread a rumour that he was gay after he rebuffed a kiss from her but the two later dated briefly in 2011. He dumped her for Evan's sister [[Jasmine Cooper|Jasmine]] (Pearl McGlashan) but cheated on Jasmine when he had a one-night stand with [[Suzy McRae|Suzy]] (Maisey McSwiney). Phoenix was shocked when Jasmine died for several minutes on his lap due to her [[Long QT syndrome]] and later struggled to cope with her newfound morbid personality causing the two to break up numerous times. Phoenix ultimately ended the relationship when he developed an unrequited crush on [[List of Shortland Street characters (2012)#Megan Reynolds|Megan]] (Lira Edwards). Phoenix was shocked when Chris was arrested for the murder of his school tutor, [[Hayley O'Neill]] (Michelle Blundell) and struggled to accept his protest of innocence. However he ended up freeing his father when Hayley's true killer [[Drew Webster (Shortland Street)|Drew]] (Joel Herbert) kidnapped him and confessed. In 2013 Phoenix began to date popular schoolgirl [[List of Shortland Street characters (2013)#Britney Buchanan|Britney Buchanan]] (Eliza McKay) but the two broke up after meddling from new girl, [[Dayna Jenkins]] (Lucy Elliott). Phoenix soon turned against his family lifestyle and took up street art to express his true beliefs. This however lead to near legal trouble and in November, Phoenix decided to leave Ferndale to study at a Berlin university for art. Only a month after his departure, Chris revealed that Phoenix had dropped out of the school and had taken to traveling the world. In 2014, Chris stated that Phoenix would not be returning for his wedding but would rather attend via video chat.\n\nPhoenix unexpectedly returned to Ferndale 6 years after his departure and shocked Chris by introducing his heavily pregnant girlfriend [[Tess Hutchison (Shortland Street)|Tess]] (Becky McEwen). Chris soon realised that Phoenix had struggled in Berlin as an artist and was owing significant amounts of money. He hired him as an office administrator much to Phoenix's angst. Tess and Phoenix newborn daughter was born on 2019 season finale they decided to name her Ameila Warner.\n\nAt the beginning of 2020, after being talked down by a returning [[Frank Warner (Shortland Street)|Frank Warner]] from leaving Amelia and Tess on the lurch, he decided to put his $10,000 gift from Chris to become an investor for an art gallery in New Zealand, in exchange for a feature exhibition spot. The money was supposed to be the payment for prams, nappies and a modest family car. Despite Franks' displeasure, he was still glad that Phoenix was trying to further his career (even when the investment is rather risky), rather than turning into crime like drugs and gangs, hence Frank didn't turn him in to Tess or Chris.\n\nIn February, after a failure with the art gallery, Phoenix takes $1,000,000 from the hospital and when he confesses to Tess, he wants to make a runner with Tess and his baby. Tess calms him and tells him to stay in Ferndale but he makes a runner and was reported to be in Santiago, Chile last\n\n==Character development==\n===Characterisation===\nPhoenix was initially portrayed as a teenager who although often landed himself in bad situations, was friendly and welcoming to all those he interacted with.<ref name=mathstutor/> He earned the title \"Mr Big Dick\" however a storyline in 2012 that revolved around Phoenix developing a crush on his psychopathic maths tutor [[Hayley O'Neill]] (Michelle Blundell), saw the characterization of the character develop drastically differently. Holibar explained, \"He's grown up, he's sort of had to\". Hayley manipulated Phoenix's affections to try to get closer to his father and ended up accusing Phoenix of sadistically stalking her.<ref name=mathstutor/> This lead to Phoenix being \"angsty and angry\".<ref name=frankreturn/> Holibar enjoyed what the storyline did for his character, \"I've enjoyed it. I like getting angry and I do occasionally. It was fun playing something that wasn't just Phoenix being nice to everyone 24-7, which gets a bit boring to do. It was good to see a darker side as he starts pushing people away and not coping at all with the things going on for him.\"<ref name=mathstutor/> Upon Phoenix's return in 2019, Holibar believed \"adult Phoenix\" was \"flawed\" and was very different from the \"many years ... being very nice\" from his first stint. This conflicted with becoming a father as Phoenix, \"is thinking more of himself than his partner and his child ... and ... it's a big life shift for someone who has been thinking about himself for so long. He's still adjusting to having something more important to prioritise.\" He was said to be \"charming\" but was beginning to show his \"true character now he has no money\".<ref name=frankreturn/>\n\n==Reception==\nUpon Phoenix's arrival, Shortland Street commentator ''Throng'' was surprised such an interesting storyline twist had not already occurred.<ref name=otherchildren/> [[Hugh Sundae]] from [[The New Zealand Herald]] praised Holibar's acting and compared him positively to [[Lee Donoghue]], the actor of [[Hunter McKay]].<ref name=review>{{cite web|title=TV Review: Shortland Street|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/television/news/article.cfm?c_id=339&objectid=10663177|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|publisher=[[APN News & Media]]|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=12 December 2011|author=Sundae, Hugh}}</ref> He also stated that Holibar was already a greater actor than [[Ido Drent]] ([[Daniel Potts (Shortland Street)|Daniel Potts]]) despite only appearing in a small number of scenes.<ref name=review/> Holibar's on screen father, [[Michael Galvin]], praised Holibar - stating: He's very relaxed and very natural for someone of his age and very keen to learn, which is a very important thing on this show because it's very demanding.\"<ref name=generation/> Holibar won the \"Up and Cumming Actor\" award in the ''Showgirls King of the Pole'' competition 2011 for his role as Phoenix.<ref name=fanfavourite>{{cite web|title=Shorty is fan favourite|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/shorty-fan-favourite-4598924|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=November 2011|accessdate=12 December 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63s8sWVWs|archivedate=12 December 2011}}</ref> Upon Phoenix's return, a television columnist referred to the character as, \"Everyone's least favourite\",<ref name=granddaddy/> and \"the most Foolish Warner child\".<ref name=strumpert>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street: Strumpet Queen Leanne returns, leaving Damo in a pickle|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/118909714/shortland-street-strumpet-queen-leanne-returns-leaving-damo-in-a-pickle|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]|date=20 January 2020|author=Kate Robertson}}</ref> Another reviewer listed the return of the \"well-loved jt much maligned\" character as one of the show's \"best kept secrets\".<ref name=toptwelve>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street: 2019's most surprising moments|author=Harvey, Kerry|date=19 December 2019|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/118053966/shortland-street-2019s-most-surprising-moments}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Shortland Street}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raynor, Phoenix}}\n[[Category:Shortland Street characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2010]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox soap character\n| image = Phoenix Raynor.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| name = Phoenix Warner\n| series = [[Shortland Street]]\n| portrayer = Geordie Holibar\n| first = 2 August 2010\n| last = 25 February 2020\n| gender = Male\n| alias =Phoenix Warner\n| age = \n| classification = [[List of Shortland Street characters#Current characters|Present; recurring]]\n| born = 2 September 1995\n| death =\n| Introducer = Steven Zanoski (2010)<br>Maxine Fleming (2019)\n| years = 2010\u201313, 2019\u201320\n| occupation = Artist\n| family =\n| father= [[Chris Warner]]\n| mother= [[Alison Raynor]]\n| halfbrothers= [[Frank Warner (Shortland Street)|Frank Warner]] <br>[[Finn Warner]]<br>[[Harry Warner (character)|Harry Warner]]<br>James Warner\n| halfsisters = [[Sass Warner]]<br>[[Trinity Kwan]]\n| sisters= \n| daughters= Amelie Warner\n| sons= \n| granddaughters= \n| grandsons=\n| grandfathers= [[Bruce Warner (character)|Sir Bruce Warner]]<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (1992)#Kevin Raynor|Kevin Raynor]]\n| grandmothers= [[Margot Warner|Margot, Lady Warner]] <br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (1992)#Irene Raynor|Irene Raynor]]\n| relatives = [[Cecile Worthington]] (great aunt)<br>Desmond Worthington (great uncle)<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (2003)#Garth Worthington|Garth Worthington]] (great uncle)<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters (2010)#Brian Raynor|Brian Raynor]] (great uncle)\n| nephews=\n| nieces= \n| aunts= [[Amanda Warner]]\n| uncles= [[Guy Warner]]\n| cousins= [[Tuesday Warner]]<br>[[List of Shortland Street characters#P|Kelly Piper]] (possibly)\n}}\n\n'''Phoenix Warner''' (previously '''Raynor''')  is a fictional character on the [[New Zealand]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Shortland Street]]''. He has been portrayed by Geordie Holibar since his debut in the show's first ever 90 minute episode in August 2010. The character was introduced as the unknown son of long-standing character [[Chris Warner]] ([[Michael Galvin]]) and ex-wife [[Alison Raynor]] ([[Danielle Cormack]]).\n\n==Creation and casting==\nAfter creating the role, producers researched baby name trends throughout the nineties and decided upon the name; \"Phoenix\".<ref name=namegame>{{cite web|title=The Name Game|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/name-game-4984349|work=[[Shortland Street]]|publisher=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=24 July 2012|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69OE1kf5q|archivedate=24 July 2012}}</ref> Geordie Holibar, the grandson of former ''Shortland Street'' actor [[Liddy Holloway]] was cast<ref name=block>{{cite web |url= http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/new-kid-block-3688541 |title= New kid on the block - Shortland Street |publisher= [[Television New Zealand]] |accessdate= 3 October 2011|date=August 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63s8XyVKi|archivedate=12 December 2011}}</ref> and the character made his debut in the show's first-ever feature-length episode on 2 August 2010.<ref name=otherchildren>{{cite web |url= http://www.throng.co.nz/shortland-street/chris-warner-finally-has-other-children |title= Chris Warner finally has other children |publisher= Throng |date= 3 August 2010 |accessdate= 3 October 2011}}</ref> Holibar's uncle [[Joel Tobeck]] helped him prepare for the role as he had previously appeared in the mid-1990s.<ref name=generation>{{cite journal|title=Generation game|journal=New Zealand TV Guide|date=19 August 2010|author=Nealon, Sarah}}</ref> Initially Holibar shared a lot of scenes with on screen father, [[Michael Galvin]], but as his storylines developed, he ended up spending a lot more scenes with the fellow teenage characters.<ref name=settling>{{cite web|title=Settling into the Street|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/settling-into-street-4039563|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=February 2011|accessdate=12 December 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63s9IBsuC|archivedate=12 December 2011}}</ref> Holibar enjoyed acting alongside people his age, saying; \"I have lots of fun with Frankie [Adams] ([[Ula Levi]]), Tyler [Read] ([[Evan Cooper (Shortland Street)|Evan Cooper]]) and Pearl [McGlashan] ([[Jasmine Cooper]]). It's been cool working with people your own age because you know that you're all going through the same kind of thing.\"<ref name=settling/> Holibar noted the help he received from long time cast members, Galvin and [[Angela Bloomfield]], \"It's good just working with him and Angela who have been on the show for so long and they know where the cameras are, they know not to block your light. They know all the tricks.\"<ref name=mathstutor>{{cite journal|title=Maths tutor turns tables on Phoenix|journal=New Zealand TV Guide|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=19 April 2012|author=Smith, Janie}}</ref> Phoenix departed the show in 2013.<ref name=depart>{{cite web|title=Riding in Cars show coming to the North island|date=4 November 2016|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11741645}}</ref>\n\nHolibar reprised his role in 2019, with the character returning on 5 December 2019.<ref name=granddaddy>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street: Chris Warner is about to be a grandaddy|author=Robertson, Kate|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/118050274/shortland-street-chris-warner-is-about-to-be-a-grandaddy|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]}}</ref> Holibar had not returned to the set since departing 6 years beforehand but felt \"super welcome\" filming his first scenes.<ref name=return>{{cite web|title=Geordie Holibar returns as Phoenix Warner!|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/shows/shortland-street/cast/geordie-holibar|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=6 December 2019}}</ref> The character of Phoenix was said to undergo a more \"flawed\" character arc upon returning.<ref name=frankreturn>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street returns with Frank Warner's homecoming|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/tv-guide/118405740/shortland-street-returns-with-frank-warners-homecoming|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]|date=6 January 2020|author=Harvey, Kerry|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]}}</ref> Holibar departed the soap again on 25th February 2020 after Phoenix steals 1 millon dollars from the hospital leaving Tess and his daughter behind.\n\n==Storylines==\nPhoenix was born to [[Alison Raynor]] ([[Danielle Cormack]]) and her divorced husband, [[Chris Warner]] ([[Michael Galvin]]). Alison decided to keep Phoenix a secret from Chris and the two lived in America. After Alison grew sick of the American schooling system, she and Phoenix travelled to New Zealand and lived on a farm. In November 2009 Alison died on a yacht and Phoenix was taken in by her uncle [[Brian Raynor|Brian]] ([[Ian Mune]]).\n\nChris learnt in August 2010 that Phoenix was his son and, after a DNA test, he adopted him. Phoenix struggled to get on with half brother [[Harry Warner (Shortland Street)|Harry]] ([[Reid Walker]]) but befriended [[Evan Cooper (character)|Evan Cooper]] (Tyler Read). New girl [[Ula Levi]] (Frankie Adams) spread a rumour that he was gay after he rebuffed a kiss from her but the two later dated briefly in 2011. He dumped her for Evan's sister [[Jasmine Cooper|Jasmine]] (Pearl McGlashan) but cheated on Jasmine when he had a one-night stand with [[Suzy McRae|Suzy]] (Maisey McSwiney). Phoenix was shocked when Jasmine died for several minutes on his lap due to her [[Long QT syndrome]] and later struggled to cope with her newfound morbid personality causing the two to break up numerous times. Phoenix ultimately ended the relationship when he developed an unrequited crush on [[List of Shortland Street characters (2012)#Megan Reynolds|Megan]] (Lira Edwards). Phoenix was shocked when Chris was arrested for the murder of his school tutor, [[Hayley O'Neill]] (Michelle Blundell) and struggled to accept his protest of innocence. However he ended up freeing his father when Hayley's true killer [[Drew Webster (Shortland Street)|Drew]] (Joel Herbert) kidnapped him and confessed. In 2013 Phoenix began to date popular schoolgirl [[List of Shortland Street characters (2013)#Britney Buchanan|Britney Buchanan]] (Eliza McKay) but the two broke up after meddling from new girl, [[Dayna Jenkins]] (Lucy Elliott). Phoenix soon turned against his family lifestyle and took up street art to express his true beliefs. This however lead to near legal trouble and in November, Phoenix decided to leave Ferndale to study at a Berlin university for art. Only a month after his departure, Chris revealed that Phoenix had dropped out of the school and had taken to traveling the world. In 2014, Chris stated that Phoenix would not be returning for his wedding but would rather attend via video chat.\n\nPhoenix unexpectedly returned to Ferndale 6 years after his departure and shocked Chris by introducing his heavily pregnant girlfriend [[Tess Hutchison (Shortland Street)|Tess]] (Becky McEwen). Chris soon realised that Phoenix had struggled in Berlin as an artist and was owing significant amounts of money. He hired him as an office administrator much to Phoenix's angst. Tess and Phoenix newborn daughter was born on 2019 season finale they decided to name her Ameila Warner.\n\nAt the beginning of 2020, after being talked down by a returning [[Frank Warner (Shortland Street)|Frank Warner]] from leaving Amelia and Tess on the lurch, he decided to put his $10,000 gift from Chris to become an investor for an art gallery in New Zealand, in exchange for a feature exhibition spot. The money was supposed to be the payment for prams, nappies and a modest family car. Despite Franks' displeasure, he was still glad that Phoenix was trying to further his career (even when the investment is rather risky), rather than turning into crime like drugs and gangs, hence Frank didn't turn him in to Tess or Chris.\n\nIn February, after a failure with the art gallery, Phoenix takes $1,000,000 from the hospital and when he confesses to Tess, he wants to make a runner with Tess and his baby. Tess calms him and tells him to stay in Ferndale but he makes a runner and was reported to be in Santiago, Chile last\n\n==Character development==\n===Characterisation===\nPhoenix was initially portrayed as a teenager who although often landed himself in bad situations, was friendly and welcoming to all those he interacted with.<ref name=mathstutor/> He earned the title \"Mr Nice Guy\" however a storyline in 2012 that revolved around Phoenix developing a crush on his psychopathic maths tutor [[Hayley O'Neill]] (Michelle Blundell), saw the characterization of the character develop drastically differently. Holibar explained, \"He's grown up, he's sort of had to\". Hayley manipulated Phoenix's affections to try to get closer to his father and ended up accusing Phoenix of sadistically stalking her.<ref name=mathstutor/> This lead to Phoenix being \"angsty and angry\".<ref name=frankreturn/> Holibar enjoyed what the storyline did for his character, \"I've enjoyed it. I like getting angry and I do occasionally. It was fun playing something that wasn't just Phoenix being nice to everyone 24-7, which gets a bit boring to do. It was good to see a darker side as he starts pushing people away and not coping at all with the things going on for him.\"<ref name=mathstutor/> Upon Phoenix's return in 2019, Holibar believed \"adult Phoenix\" was \"flawed\" and was very different from the \"many years ... being very nice\" from his first stint. This conflicted with becoming a father as Phoenix, \"is thinking more of himself than his partner and his child ... and ... it's a big life shift for someone who has been thinking about himself for so long. He's still adjusting to having something more important to prioritise.\" He was said to be \"charming\" but was beginning to show his \"true character now he has no money\".<ref name=frankreturn/>\n\n==Reception==\nUpon Phoenix's arrival, Shortland Street commentator ''Throng'' was surprised such an interesting storyline twist had not already occurred.<ref name=otherchildren/> [[Hugh Sundae]] from [[The New Zealand Herald]] praised Holibar's acting and compared him positively to [[Lee Donoghue]], the actor of [[Hunter McKay]].<ref name=review>{{cite web|title=TV Review: Shortland Street|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/television/news/article.cfm?c_id=339&objectid=10663177|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|publisher=[[APN News & Media]]|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=12 December 2011|author=Sundae, Hugh}}</ref> He also stated that Holibar was already a greater actor than [[Ido Drent]] ([[Daniel Potts (Shortland Street)|Daniel Potts]]) despite only appearing in a small number of scenes.<ref name=review/> Holibar's on screen father, [[Michael Galvin]], praised Holibar - stating: He's very relaxed and very natural for someone of his age and very keen to learn, which is a very important thing on this show because it's very demanding.\"<ref name=generation/> Holibar won the \"Up and Coming Actor\" award in the ''Girlfriend Faves Forever'' competition 2011 for his role as Phoenix.<ref name=fanfavourite>{{cite web|title=Shorty is fan favourite|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/shortland-street/shorty-fan-favourite-4598924|work=[[Television New Zealand]]|date=November 2011|accessdate=12 December 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63s8sWVWs|archivedate=12 December 2011}}</ref> Upon Phoenix's return, a television columnist referred to the character as, \"Everyone's least favourite\",<ref name=granddaddy/> and \"the most Foolish Warner child\".<ref name=strumpert>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street: Strumpet Queen Leanne returns, leaving Damo in a pickle|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/118909714/shortland-street-strumpet-queen-leanne-returns-leaving-damo-in-a-pickle|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]|date=20 January 2020|author=Kate Robertson}}</ref> Another reviewer listed the return of the \"well-loved\" character as one of the show's \"best kept secrets\".<ref name=toptwelve>{{cite web|title=Shortland Street: 2019's most surprising moments|author=Harvey, Kerry|date=19 December 2019|work=[[stuff.co.nz]]|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/118053966/shortland-street-2019s-most-surprising-moments}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Shortland Street}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raynor, Phoenix}}\n[[Category:Shortland Street characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2010]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "203.211.114.65", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenix_Warner"}
{"title_page": "Sterling K. Brown", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sterling K. Brown\n| image              = Sterling K. Brown by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Brown at the 2018 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = Sterling Kelby Brown\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|4|5}}\n| birth_place        = [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| education          = [[Stanford University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}} <br>[[New York University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2001\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Olivette, Missouri]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Ryan Michelle Bathe]]|2007}}\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Sterling K. Brown|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Sterling Kelby Brown''' (born April 5, 1976)<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/sterling-k-brown| title= Sterling K. Brown: Television Actor, Film Actor (1976\u2013)|publisher=[[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]| accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref> is an American actor. He has portrayed [[Christopher Darden]] in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] limited series ''[[The People v. O. J. Simpson: American Crime Story]]'' (2016) and starred as [[List of This Is Us characters#Randall Pearson|Randall Pearson]] in the [[NBC]] drama series ''[[This Is Us (TV series)|This Is Us]]'' (2016\u2013present). Both roles have earned him [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s and the latter also won him a [[Golden Globe Award]]. Brown has also played supporting roles in the films ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' (2018) and ''[[Waves (film)|Waves]]'' (2019), and his most recent role was that of manager for \u201cShy Baldwin,\u201d fictitious character on [[Amazon Prime]]\u2019s original series ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]] ''.\n\n==Early life==\nBrown was born in 1976 in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], to Sterling Brown<ref name=biography.com /> and Aralean Banks Brown. Brown is one of five children; he has two sisters and two brothers.<ref name=tvg>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20170808160401/http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/sterling-k-brown/bio/193898/ Sterling K. Brown Biography]\". ''[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]]''. Archived from [http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/sterling-k-brown/bio/193898/  the original] on August 8, 2017.</ref> His father died when Brown was 10 years old.<ref name=people09-21-2016 /> As a child, he went by the name Kelby; when he turned 16 he adopted the name Sterling, explaining in 2016,\n{{Cquote|I went by Kelby. My mom tells me this story \u2013 she was reiterating it the other day \u2013 in kindergarten I came home one day and said, 'Mom, Sterling is eight letters and Kelby is five. I'll just do Kelby and then when I turn 16, I will go by Sterling.' And I don't remember that. The impetus for me is that he had been gone for some time, and I was like, 'Kelby was a little boy's name.' I felt like I was ready to become Sterling.<ref name=people09-21-2016>Stone, Natalie (September 21, 2016). \"[http://people.com/tv/sterling-k-brown-reveals-why-he-changed-his-name-as-a-teenager/ Sterling K. Brown Reveals Why He Changed His Name As a Teenager]\". ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''. [[Time Inc.]] Retrieved on October 8, 2016.</ref>}}\n\nBrown grew up in [[Olivette, Missouri]], an inner-ring suburb of St. Louis - located in St. Louis, County, and attended [[Mary Institute and St. Louis Country Day School]].<ref name=SLPD020216>Pennington, Gail (February 2, 2016). \"[http://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/television/gail-pennington/st-louisan-relives-simpson-trial-in-people-v-o-j/article_422f0f08-3c68-514c-99c9-f9f37f45e437.html St. Louisan relives Simpson trial in 'People v. O.J.']\". ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]''. [[Lee Enterprises]]. Retrieved on October 25, 2016..</ref>\n\nBrown graduated from [[Stanford University]] in 1998 with an acting degree. He initially wanted to major in economics so he could work in business, but he fell in love with acting as a college freshman.<ref name= atcountryday>{{cite news|last=Pennington|first=Gail|date=August 18, 2005|title=At Country Day, Brown exited stage right into acting|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|page=F1|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47453533/|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Brown then attended [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]] where he graduated with a [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree.<ref name=Stanford091011>{{cite journal|url=http://alumni.stanford.edu/get/page/magazine/article/?article_id=44011|work=Stanford Magazine|title=Now Playing|department=Screen Scene|first=Laura|last=Shin|date=September 2011|accessdate=October 8, 2016|archivedate=January 4, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6wE4Ojxoh?url=https://alumni.stanford.edu/get/page/magazine/article/?article_id=44011|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from college, Brown performed in a series of roles in regional theater.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dominguez|first=Robert|date=June 20, 2001|title= 'Colony' Cruel and Unusual|work=[[New York Daily News]]|page=38|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47456766/colony-cruel-and-unusual|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>Otten, Ted (September 19, 2001). \"McCarter courts with 'Romeo and Juliet'\". ''The Times''. (Trenton, New Jersey).</ref><ref>Kilpatrick, Gloria M. (June 3, 2002). \"Hangar Opens Season with Powerful 'Topdog': The Play Explores the Relationship of Two Brothers Struggling to Get By\". ''The Post-Standard'' (Syracuse, New York). p. 18.</ref><ref>Gerteiny, Elizabeth (July 1, 2004). \"'Someone' brings intensity, brilliance to stage\". ''The Weston Forum'' (Weston, Connecticut). p. A15.</ref><ref>De La Vina, Mark (September 9, 1997). \"Survival and the Blues in Drama of 1930 Harlem\". ''The Mercury News'' (San Jose, California). p.1E.</ref> Brown has also since appeared in numerous television shows including ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', ''[[NYPD Blue]]'',<ref name= atcountryday /> ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'', ''[[Boston Legal]]'', ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'', ''[[Without A Trace]]'', ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]'',<ref>:Best Bets\". ''American Press'' (Lake Charles, Louisiana). October 6, 2006. p. 63.</ref> and ''[[Third Watch]]''.<ref>\"'Starved' finds comedy in eating disorders\". ''The York Dispatch'' (York, Pennsylvania). August 3, 2005.</ref> Brown was a regular in the comedy ''[[Starved]]'',<ref>Moore, Frazier (August 2, 2005). \"'Starved' Finds Laughs in Eating Disorders\". ''Associated Press''.</ref> and he has also appeared in movies, including ''[[Stay (2005 film)|Stay]]'' with [[Ewan McGregor]], ''[[Brown Sugar (2002 film)|Brown Sugar]]'' with [[Taye Diggs]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Kevin D. |date=June 3, 2007|title='Army Wives' Recruiting Audience|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]] (TV Post)|location=[[Palm Beach, Florida]]|page=3|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47449756/army-wives-recruiting-audience/|via=[[Ancestry.com#Newspapers.com|Newspapers.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> and ''[[Trust the Man]]'' with [[David Duchovny]] and [[Julianne Moore]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Sandi |date=September 1, 2006|title=Couple troubles create laughs and drama in 'Trust the Man'|work=[[The Oklahoman]]|location=[[Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]]|page=7D| url=https://oklahoman.com/article/2839775/couple-troubles-create-laughs-and-drama-in-trust-the-man}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nBrown played a recurring character on the television series ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]'', where he portrayed vampire hunter Gordon Walker.<ref>\"TV Watch\". ''Hampshire Gazette'' (Northampton, Massachusetts). October 12, 2006.</ref> Brown played Dr. Roland Burton on ''[[Army Wives]]''.<ref>\"Lifetime to deploy \u2018Army Wives'\". ''Ventura County Star'' (Ventura, California). December 7, 2006.</ref> He portrayed Detective Cal Beecher on ''[[Person of Interest (TV series)|Person of Interest]]'',<ref>\"Review: Reese and Finch find The Person of Interest 'In Extremis'\". ''Columbus Examiner'' (Columbus, Ohio). April 26, 2013.</ref> also appearing on the show ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]''. In 2008, he played David Mosley on the \"Patience\" episode of ''[[Eli Stone]]''. In 2016, Brown starred in the FX miniseries ''[[The People v. O. J. Simpson: American Crime Story|The People v. O.J. Simpson: American Crime Story]]'' as [[Christopher Darden]],<ref>\"In the Spotlight: FX's 'American Crime Story'. Dramatizes the O.J. Simpson Trial\". ''The Newport Daily Express'' (Newport, Vermont). p. 11.</ref> for which he won the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie]] at the [[68th Primetime Emmy Awards]].<ref>\"[http://www.people.com/people/package/article/0,,21026212_21030833,00.html People v. O.J. Simpson Star Sterling K. Brown Chokes Up While Dedicating Emmy to His Late Father]. ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''. Retrieved September 19, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn the theater, Brown was cast in the 2002 production of [[Bertolt Brecht]]'s ''[[The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui]]'' starring [[Al Pacino]], [[Paul Giamatti]], [[Steve Buscemi]], [[John Goodman]] and [[Jacqueline McKenzie]].<ref>Isherwood, Charles (October 21, 2002). \"[https://variety.com/2002/legit/reviews/the-resistible-rise-of-arturo-ui-3-1200545356/#! The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui]\". ''Variety''.</ref> In 2014, he starred as Hero in [[Suzan-Lori Parks]]' [[Odyssey]]-inspired play ''Father Comes Home From the Wars'' at New York's [[Public Theater]].<ref name=\"vreview\">Green, Jesse (October 28, 2014). \"[http://www.vulture.com/2014/10/theater-review-father-comes-home-from-the-wars.html Theater Review: Father Comes Home From the Wars]\". ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''.</ref><ref>Feldberg, Robert (October 29, 2014). \"A Slave's Odyssey in Three Acts\". ''Herald News'' (Woodland Park, New Jersey). p. D1.</ref> Brown also starred in the 2014 movie ''The Suspect'' with [[Mekhi Phifer]].<ref>Longsdorf, Amy (April 25, 2014). \"New on DVD This Week: April 25\". ''Herald News'' (Woodland Park, New Jersey). p. D4.</ref> \n \nSince 2016, Brown has starred in the television series ''[[This Is Us (TV series)|This Is Us]]''.<ref>Pennington, Gail (May 15, 2016). \"NBC finalizes fall schedule with three new series\". ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch''.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OUTSTANDING LEAD ACTOR IN A DRAMA SERIES - 2017|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2017/outstanding-lead-actor-in-a-drama-series|website=Emmys|publisher=emmys.com|accessdate=October 24, 2017}}</ref>In 2018, he became the first African-American actor to win a [[Golden Globe]] in the best actor in a television drama category, which he won for ''This Is Us''.<ref>Respers, Lisa (2018). \"[http://www.cnn.com/2018/01/07/entertainment/golden-globes-2018/index.html Golden Globes 2018: A night of firsts]\". ''CNN''. Retrieved January 8, 2018.</ref> That same year he also became the first African-American actor to win a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] in the Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series category, also for ''This Is Us'' and appeared in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' as N'Jobu.<ref>\"[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/sag-awards-2018-sterling-brown-makes-history/story?id=52507971 SAG Awards 2018: Sterling K. Brown makes history again]\". ''ABC News''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> He also was part of that year's Screen Actors Guild Award win for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series, again for ''This Is Us''.<ref>\"[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/sag-awards-2018-woman-takes-home-award/story?id=52507448 SAG Awards 2018: 'Veep,' 'This Is Us' and 'Three Billboards Outside Ebbing, Missouri' win big]\". ''ABC News''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Brown gave the commencement address at [[Stanford University]].<ref>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2018/06/17/sterling-k-brown-stanford-university-commencement-address-2018/708578002/ 'This is Us' star Sterling K. Brown delivers Stanford University commencement]\". ''USA Today''. June 17, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Brown was announced in [[D23 Expo]] and Twitter to voice Lieutenant Destin Mattias in ''[[Frozen II]]''.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=DisneyFrozen|number=1165346863685353472|date=24 August 2019|title=Just Announced: @SterlingKBrown (Lieutenant Matthias) and @EvanRachelWood (Queen Iduna) have joined the cast of #Frozen2, coming to theaters November 22. #D23Expo|author=Disney's Frozen 2|accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=SterlingKBrown|number=1166061731971358721|title=Lieutenant Destin Mattias reporting for duty! Excited to finally share with you that I\u2019ll be joining the coolest crew for #Frozen2.|website=Twitter|author=Sterling K Brown|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=alittlejelee|number=1166917484789682177|title=Many have been asking me about spelling and title. Meet Lieutenant Destin Mattias.|author=Jennifer Lee|date=August 29, 2019|accessdate=August 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn June 2007, Brown married actress [[Ryan Michelle Bathe]], whom he met as a college freshman at Stanford.<ref name= atcountryday/> They have two sons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/love/6-things-sterling-k-brown-ryan-michelle-bathe-love|title=6 Things To Know About Sterling K. Brown And His Wife Ryan Michelle Bathe Love Story|work=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|last=Porter|first=Lauren|date=September 19, 2016|accessdate=February 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/03/09/this-is-us-sterling-k-brown-feels-blessed-beyond-words/|title=\u2018This Is Us\u2019: Former Bay Area resident Sterling K. Brown feels \u2018blessed beyond words\u2019|date=March 9, 2017|work=[[The Mercury News]]|publisher=[[Digital First Media]]|first=Chuck|last=Barney|accessdate=September 16, 2017|archivedate= September 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916094931/https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/03/09/this-is-us-sterling-k-brown-feels-blessed-beyond-words/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Director !! Notes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Brown Sugar (2002 film)|Brown Sugar]]'' || Co-worker || [[Rick Famuyiwa]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2005 || ''[[Trust the Man]]'' || Rand || [[Bart Freundlich]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Stay (2005 film)|Stay]]'' || Frederick / Devon || [[Marc Forster]] ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Righteous Kill]]'' || Rogers || [[Jon Avnet]] ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Our Idiot Brother]]'' || Officer Omar Coleman || [[Jesse Peretz]] ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[The Suspect (2013 American film)|The Suspect]]'' || The Other Suspect || Stuart Connelly ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Mojave (film)|Mojave]]'' || Detective Fletcher || [[William Monahan]] || Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2016 || ''[[Whiskey Tango Foxtrot (film)|Whiskey Tango Foxtrot]]'' || Sgt. Hurd || [[Glenn Ficarra]]<br>[[John Requa]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Spaceman (2016 film)|Spaceman]]'' || Rodney Scott || Brett Rapkin ||\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Marshall (film)|Marshall]]'' || Joseph Spell || [[Reginald Hudlin]] || \n|-\n| rowspan=3|2018 || ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' || N'Jobu || [[Ryan Coogler]] || \n|-\n|''[[Hotel Artemis]]'' ||Sherman (\"Waikiki\")  || [[Drew Pearce]] || \n|-\n|''[[The Predator (film)|The Predator]]'' || Will Traeger || [[Shane Black]] || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2019 || ''[[The Angry Birds Movie 2]]'' || Garry ||[[Thurop Van Orman]] || Voice\n|-\n| ''[[Waves (film)|Waves]]'' || Ronald Williams ||[[Trey Edward Shults]] || \n|-\n|''[[Frozen II]]'' || Lieutenant Destin Mattias || [[Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)|Jennifer Lee]]<br>[[Chris Buck]] || Voice\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2020 || ''[[The Rhythm Section]]'' || Frank White || [[Reed Morano]] ||\n|-\n|''[[Rise (2020 film)|Rise]]'' || Willie Davis || [[Kevin Rodney Sullivan]] || \n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2002\u201304 || ''[[Third Watch]]'' || Officer Edward Dade || 9 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2003 || ''[[Hack (TV series)|Hack]]'' || Rasheed Morgan || Episode: \"Hidden Agenda\"\n|-\n || ''[[Tarzan (2003 TV series)|Tarzan]]'' || Detective Carey || 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2004 || ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' || Bob Harris || Episode: \"Get Carter\"\n|-\n || ''[[NYPD Blue]]'' || Kelvin George || Episode: \"Chatty Chatty Bang Bang\"\n|-\n || ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'' || Sgt. Harry Smith || Episode: \"Coming Home\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2005 || ''[[Boston Legal]]'' || Zeke Borns || Episode: \"Death Be Not Proud\"\n|-\n || ''[[Starved]]'' || Adam Williams || 7 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2006 || ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'' || Agent Rance || Episode: \"There's Only One Sidney Bristow\"\n|-\n || ''[[Smith (TV series)|Smith]]'' || Mr. Corey || Episode: \"Three\"\n|-\n || ''[[Without a Trace]]'' || Thomas Biggs || Episode: \"Watch Over Me\"\n|-\n| 2006\u201307 || ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]'' || Gordon Walker || 4 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2007 || ''[[Shark (U.S. TV series)|Shark]]'' || Quenton North || Episode: \"Teacher's Pet\"\n|-\n || ''[[Standoff (TV series)|Standoff]]'' || Russell Marsh || Episode: \"Lie to Me\"\n|-\n| 2007\u201313 || ''[[Army Wives]]'' || Roland Burton || 107 episodes\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Eli Stone]]'' || David Mosley || Episode: \"Patience\"\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]'' || Todd Gillis || Episode